entry.title: Fix the crash caused by CHECK for the url comparison
entry.content:
This is the fix CL for the crash bug in crbug.com/1492640. The crash is

caused by CHECK_EQ(), which checks if the deduped request URL is same as

the one from the network request triggered for the race request.



We identified the crash happens when the request is intercepted by some

extensions e.g. ad blockers. They are able to change the deduped URL

from `https://~` to `chrome-extension://`. We compare the changed URL

with the original start url, and that hits CHECK error.



This URLLoaderFactory just fuses two mojo endpoints into one. That can

be called multiple times inside the blink's ThrottlingURLLoader [1].

Also this URLLoaderFactory is used only when the corresponding request

from the fetch handler is detected. As far as the detection is baesd on

the base::UnguessableToken match, we can trust that the upcoming request

is same as the network request dispatched for the race. We don't have to

have additional the URL comparison, which caused this crash.



This URLLoaderFactory was designed to work for the dedupe by fusing

pipes, but when the request is respond with the internal redirect and

the new url starts with the exntesion prorocol, the force restart of

throttling_url_loader is called and CreateLoaderAndStart() in

ServiceWorkerForwardedRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderFactory can be called

multiple times [2]. This CL addressed that case by changing the

URLLoaderFactory initiates the new request when CreateLoaderAndStart()

is called but the message pipes are already fused.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/common/loader/throttling_url_loader.cc;l=607

[2] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/renderer/platform/loader/fetch/url_loader/resource_request_sender.cc;l=644



Bug: 1492640

Change-Id: I353c491fdfb6835a0a6aef43a4c7e8c47a0bc921

entry.title: Remove unused policy opcode definitions
entry.content:
The policy opcode engine lives deep in the sandbox and is used to

match function parameters on the stack before allowing or denying

calls proxied by the sandbox broker.



The engine 'supports' a number of operations which were never

implemented or are no longer used (policy_engine_opcodes.h):



Ops:



OP_NUMBER_MATCH_RANGE



Statuses:



GIVE_READONLY,

GIVE_ALLACCESS,

GIVE_CACHED,

GIVE_FIRST,

TERMINATE_PROCESS,



Additionally string matching allowed for case-sensitive and

case-insensitive matching but in practice only case-insensitive

matching was ever used. This option-type and related parameters

are removed. Some tests are changed to use case-insensitive matching

as those tests concern construction of opcode sequences rather than

the implementation of the match opcodes themselves.



Bug: 1023583

entry.title: [CloudOpenMetrics] Keep track of both Drive/OneDrive metrics
entry.content:
There is a Drive and OneDrive version of every metric, for example the

TaskResult metric is logged with

FileBrowser.OfficeFiles.TaskResult.Drive or

FileBrowser.OfficeFiles.TaskResult.GoogleDrive.MetricState.



Create a Metric object for each version and log with the one that

corresponds with the current `cloud_provider_` in the new method

CloudOpenMetrics::LogAndCheckForInconsistency().



The motivation is to have a history of any metrics logged under the

old cloud provider if the cloud provider changes. In a follow up CL,

the metrics under the old cloud provider can be marked as inconsistent,

as no metrics should be logged before a cloud provider change.



Introduce CloudOpenMetrics::CheckForInconsistencies() to do the

destructor consistency checks for either to Drive or OneDrive versions

of the metrics. E.g. if Drive is the cloud provider, all the consistency

checks are done assuming the whole cloud upload flow uses the Drive

cloud provider.

entry.title: [IP Protection] Refactor how proxy SSLConfig(s) get created
entry.content:
This CL doesn't introduce any functional changes but introduces some

changes and renames that will be helpful for ultimately introducing

support for nested proxies.



At the higher levels of the stack, a base SSLConfig for use by proxies

is created, and this gets updated based on per-proxy HTTP server

properties later on. This CL renames the base SSLConfig from

`proxy_ssl_config` to `base_proxy_ssl_config` to better reflect that

the SSLConfig that will ultimately be used is specific to a given

proxy.



Also, this CL moves the per-proxy customization of the SSLConfig

to the ConnectFactoryJob layer.



For more info, see:

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NKh2dFLI0NAQq4xZynLHX1Ixw5jJOq3eyR1L_-bXcSU/edit#bookmark=id.5li7wiskgerh

entry.title: [Extensions] Allow extensions to set userVisibleOnly false in workers.
entry.content:
This loosens a push policy restriction, the approval for this was

discussed/granted at:

https://groups.google.com/a/google.com/g/chrome-extensions-team-core/c/XrNq2qxNXeo/m/b573-D4pBQAJ



This allows extensions to use push messages as a background/silent

communication method that doesn't require a persistent connection for

those that use service workers.



Developer facing aspects of the change are that it allows extension

workers to pass userVisibleOnly false to

self.registration.pushManager.subscribe(...) calls without throwing an

error.



If the extension sets userVisibleOnly to false, then the user visible

notification requirement is skipped. If the extension sets

userVisibleOnly to true, then the user visible notification requirement

is respected as it was before.



One may think we need to check for the notification permission in this

CL but that doesn't seem necessary because it is handled upstream. For

context, the notification permission is required for new subscriptions

to a push server or for push messages to be received.



In practice the above means that on a subscribe attempt without the

notification permission the developer will receive an error

(mojom::PushRegistrationStatus::PERMISSION_DENIED). On receipt of a push

message without the notification permission the message will not get to

the extension background script. This is because the message will

silently fail as the subscription gets invalidated on loss of the

notification permission.



Fixed: 1319986

entry.title: Retain an AnimationClock per-document instead of per-page
entry.content:
Since each document coarsens timestamps differently, having a clock

for each makes more sense than having one per the all page and then

coarsening when retrieving the time.



Coarsening on the getter was causing a performance regression, so

coarsening at the start of the frame when setting the clock fixes it,

but requires a separate clock per document.



We still keep the page clock for things like SVG images and intersection

stability, though that can be removed in the future.



This also matches the spec more closely, where time is coarsened

when updating the rendering rather than in DocumentTimeline.currentTime.

The $build/flakiness property is being generated unconditionally with

entry.title: Break dependency cycle in Mac background downloader
entry.content:
The background downloader shared session manages a delegate through an

ARC pointer while delegate holds callbacks to bound with

scoped_refptrs to the shared session. This creates a dependency cycle

in which neither class could be destructed.



This can be solved by binding weak pointers instead of scoped_refptrs

for the delegate callbacks. Adding a WeakPtrFactory revealed that the

destruction of the shared session could occur on an arbitrary

sequence, which is prone to races. To address this, the shared session

was refactored to be created, operated, and destroyed on a single

sequence via base::SequenceBound.



BUG=1493709

`queryPermission()` could return `PermissionStatus::ASK`; only when

`requestPermission()` is called, the persistent permission status would

be retrieved for auto-granting. However, this could be a confusing

behavior to API users, as the persistence of permission is

implementation detail.



`FileSystemAccessPermissionGrant.GetStatus()` is now updated to read

from persisted grant objects and to return the combined state between

active and persisted grants. This method is used not only for

`queryPermission()` API, but also in various places internally such as

returning child handles from a parent directory handle.



Instead of introducing a new `GetPersistedStatus()`, the existing

`GetStatus()` is updated to account for persistent permission.

Additionally, a new private method `GetActivePermissionStatus()` is

introduced to replace the former usage of `GetStatus()` within

`ChromeFileSystemAccessPermissionContext`.

entry.title: Check context status before recreating platform destination
entry.content:
Changing the channel count in the RealtimeAudioDestinationHandler will

trigger the recreation of the platform destination. This in turn can

activate the audio rendering thread.



This CL adds a check to prevent this from happening after the handler

is garbage collected.
